[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] The **`ShadowRoot`** interface of the Shadow DOM API is the root node of a DOM subtree that is rendered separately from a document's main DOM tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] You can retrieve a reference to an element's shadow root using its `Element.shadowRoot` property, provided it was created using `Element.attachShadow()` with the `mode` option set to `open`.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` within the shadow tree that has focus.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Add an array of constructed stylesheets to be used by the shadow DOM subtree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] These may be shared with other DOM subtrees that share the same parent `Document` node, and the document itself.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root is clonable.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns the `CustomElementRegistry` object associated with this shadow root, or `null` if one has not been set.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root delegates focus if a non-focusable node is selected.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] The element that's currently in full screen mode for this shadow tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns a reference to the DOM element the `ShadowRoot` is attached to.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Sets or returns a reference to the DOM tree inside the `ShadowRoot`.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] The mode of the `ShadowRoot`, either `open` or `closed`.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] This defines whether or not the shadow root's internal features are accessible from JavaScript.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` within the shadow tree that is currently being presented in picture-in-picture mode.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns the `Element` set as the target for mouse events while the pointer is locked.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] `null` if lock is pending, pointer is unlocked, or if the target is in another tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] A nullable string value that indicates the effective target of any element reference made against the shadow host from outside the host element.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] The value should be the ID of an element inside the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] If set, target references to the host element from outside the shadow DOM will cause the referenced target element to become the effective target of the reference to the host element.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] A boolean that indicates whether the shadow root is serializable.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] A serializable shadow root inside an element will be serialized by `Element.getHTML()` or `ShadowRoot.getHTML()` when its `options.serializableShadowRoots` parameter is set `true`.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] This is set when the shadow root is created.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns a string containing the type of slot assignment, either `manual` or `named`.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns a `StyleSheetList` of `CSSStyleSheet` objects for stylesheets explicitly linked into, or embedded in a shadow tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns an array of all `Animation` objects currently in effect, whose target elements are descendants of the shadow tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns a `Selection` object representing the range of text selected by the user, or the current position of the caret.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns the topmost element at the specified coordinates.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Returns an array of all elements at the specified coordinates.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Provides an XSS-safe method to parse and sanitize a string of HTML into a `DocumentFragment`, which then replaces the existing tree in the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Parses a string of HTML into a document fragment, without sanitization, which then replaces the shadowroot's original subtree.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] The HTML string may include declarative shadow roots, which would be parsed as template elements the HTML was set using `ShadowRoot.innerHTML`.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] An event fired when the node(s) contained in that slot change.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] The following snippets are taken from our life-cycle-callbacks example (see it live also), which creates an element that displays a square of a size and color specified in the element's attributes.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] Inside the `<custom-square>` element's class definition we include some life cycle callbacks that make a call to an external function, `updateStyle()`, which actually applies the size and color to the element.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] You'll see that we are passing it `this` (the custom element itself) as a parameter.
[src:web-components-advanced/api-shadowroot] In the `updateStyle()` function itself, we get a reference to the shadow DOM using `Element.shadowRoot`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] One of the key features of web components is the ability to create *custom elements*: that is, HTML elements whose behavior is defined by the web developer, that extend the set of elements available in the browser.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This article introduces custom elements, and walks through some examples.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] A custom element is implemented as a class which extends `HTMLElement` (in the case of autonomous elements) or the interface you want to customize (in the case of customized built-in elements).
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This class will not be called by you, but will be called by the browser.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Immediately after defining the class, you should register the custom element, so you can create instances of it using standard DOM practices, such as writing the element in HTML markup, calling `document.createElement()`, etc.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] In the class constructor, you can set up initial state and default values, register event listeners and perhaps create a shadow root.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] At this point, you should not inspect the element's attributes or children, or add new attributes or children.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] See Requirements for custom element constructors and reactions for the complete set of requirements.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Once your custom element is registered, the browser will call certain methods of your class when code in the page interacts with your custom element in certain ways.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] By providing an implementation of these methods, which the specification calls *lifecycle callbacks*, you can run code in response to these events.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The position of a custom element in the DOM can be manipulated just like any regular HTML element, but there are lifecycle side-effects to consider.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Each time a custom element is moved (via methods such as `Element.moveBefore()` or `Node.insertBefore()`), the `disconnectedCallback()` and `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callbacks are fired, because the element is disconnected from and reconnected to the DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] However, since these callbacks are typically used to implement any required initialization or cleanup code to run at the start or end of the element's lifecycle, running them when the element is moved (rather than removed or inserted) may cause problems with its state.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] You might for example remove some stored data that the element still needs.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] If you want to preserve the element's state, you can do so by defining a `connectedMoveCallback()` lifecycle callback inside the element class, and then using the `Element.moveBefore()` method to move the element (instead of similar methods such as `Node.insertBefore()`).
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This causes the `connectedMoveCallback()` to run instead of `connectedCallback()` and `disconnectedCallback()`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] To make a custom element available in a page, call the `define()` method of `Window.customElements`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This must start with a lowercase letter, contain a hyphen, and satisfy certain other rules listed in the specification's definition of a valid name.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The custom element's constructor function.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Only included for customized built-in elements, this is an object containing a single property `extends`, which is a string naming the built-in element to extend.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Once you've defined and registered a custom element, you can use it in your code.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The examples above register custom elements on the global `CustomElementRegistry` accessed via `Window.customElements`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This means every custom element name you register must be globally unique across the entire page.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] As applications grow and begin combining components from multiple libraries, global name collisions can become a problem — if two libraries both try to define `<my-button>`, one of them will fail.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] One way to use a scoped registry is to pass it to `Element.attachShadow()` via the `customElementRegistry` option.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] You can also associate a scoped registry after the shadow root has been created by calling `initialize()`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] For declarative shadow DOM, you can use the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute on a `<template>` element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Like built-in elements, custom elements can use HTML attributes to configure the element's behavior.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] To use attributes effectively, an element has to be able to respond to changes in an attribute's value.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is then called whenever an attribute whose name is listed in the element's `observedAttributes` property is added, modified, removed, or replaced.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Note that if the element's HTML declaration includes an observed attribute, then `attributeChangedCallback()` will be called after the attribute is initialized, when the element's declaration is parsed for the first time.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] For a complete example showing the use of `attributeChangedCallback()`, see Lifecycle callbacks in this page.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Built in HTML elements can have different *states*, such as "hover", "disabled", and "read only".
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Some of these states can be set as attributes using HTML or JavaScript, while others are internal, and cannot.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Whether external or internal, commonly these states have corresponding CSS pseudo-classes that can be used to select and style the element when it is in a particular state.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Autonomous custom elements (but not elements based on built-in elements) also allow you to define states and select against them using the `:state()` pseudo-class function.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The code below shows how this works using the example of an autonomous custom element that has an internal state `"collapsed"`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The `collapsed` state is represented as a boolean property (with setter and getter methods) that is not visible outside of the element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] To make this state selectable in CSS the custom element first calls `HTMLElement.attachInternals()` in its constructor in order to attach an `ElementInternals` object, which in turn provides access to a `CustomStateSet` through the `ElementInternals.states` property.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The setter for the (internal) collapsed state adds the *identifier* `hidden` to the `CustomStateSet` when the state is `true`, and removes it when the state is `false`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The identifier is just a string: in this case we called it `hidden`, but we could have just as easily called it `collapsed`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] We can use the identifier added to the custom element's `CustomStateSet` (`this._internals.states`) for matching the element's custom state.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This is matched by passing the identifier to the `:state()` pseudo-class.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] For example, below we select on the `hidden` state being true (and hence the element's `collapsed` state) using the `:hidden` selector, and remove the border.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The `:state()` pseudo-class can also be used within the `:host()` pseudo-class function to match a custom state within a custom element's shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Additionally, the `:state()` pseudo-class can be used after the `::part()` pseudo-element to match the shadow parts of a custom element that is in a particular state.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] There are several live examples in `CustomStateSet` showing how this works.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] In the rest of this guide we'll look at a few example custom elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] You can find the source for all these examples, and more, in the web-components-examples repository, and you can see them all live at https://mdn.github.io/web-components-examples/.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] First, we'll look at an autonomous custom element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The `<popup-info>` custom element takes an image icon and a text string as attributes, and embeds the icon into the page.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] When the icon is focused, it displays the text in a pop up information box to provide further in-context information.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] To begin with, the JavaScript file defines a class called `PopupInfo`, which extends the `HTMLElement` class.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The class definition contains the `constructor()` for the class, which always starts by calling `super()` so that the correct prototype chain is established.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Inside the method `connectedCallback()`, we define all the functionality the element will have when the element is connected to the DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] In this case we attach a shadow root to the custom element, use some DOM manipulation to create the element's internal shadow DOM structure — which is then attached to the shadow root — and finally attach some CSS to the shadow root to style it.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] We don't do this work in the constructor because an element's attributes are unavailable until it is connected to the DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] In the above example we apply styles to the shadow DOM using a `<style>` element, but you can reference an external stylesheet from a `<link>` element instead.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] In this example we'll modify the `<popup-info>` custom element to use an external stylesheet.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] It's just like the original `<popup-info>` example, except that we link to an external stylesheet using a `<link>` element, which we add to the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Note that `<link>` elements do not block paint of the shadow root, so there may be a flash of unstyled content (FOUC) while the stylesheet loads.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Many modern browsers implement an optimization for `<style>` tags either cloned from a common node or that have identical text, to allow them to share a single backing stylesheet.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] With this optimization the performance of external and internal styles should be similar.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Now let's have a look at a customized built in element example.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This example extends the built-in `<ul>` element to support expanding and collapsing the list items.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Note that this time we extend `HTMLUListElement`, rather than `HTMLElement`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] This means that we get the default behavior of a list, and only have to implement our own customizations.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] As before, most of the code is in the `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callback.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] You use a `<ul>` element as normal, but specify the name of the custom element inside the `is` attribute.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] So far we've seen only one lifecycle callback in action: `connectedCallback()`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] In the final example, `<custom-square>`, we'll see some of the others.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The `<custom-square>` autonomous custom element draws a square whose size and color are determined by two attributes, named `"size"` and `"color"`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The key function in this example is `updateStyle()` — this takes an element, gets its shadow root, finds its `<style>` element, and adds `width`, `height`, and `background-color` to the style.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The actual updates are all handled by the lifecycle callbacks.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is run whenever one of the element's attributes is changed in some way.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] As you can see from its parameters, it is possible to act on attributes individually, looking at their name, and old and new attribute values.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-custom-elements] Note that to get the `attributeChangedCallback()` callback to fire when an attribute changes, you have to observe the attributes.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] An important aspect of custom elements is encapsulation, because a custom element, by definition, is a piece of reusable functionality: it might be dropped into any web page and be expected to work.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] So it's important that code running in the page should not be able to accidentally break a custom element by modifying its internal implementation.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Shadow DOM enables you to attach a DOM tree to an element, and have the internals of this tree hidden from JavaScript and CSS running in the page.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] This article covers the basics of using the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] This article assumes you are already familiar with the concept of the DOM (Document Object Model) — a tree-like structure of connected nodes that represents the different elements and strings of text appearing in a markup document (usually an HTML document in the case of web documents).
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] You can affect the nodes in the shadow DOM in exactly the same way as non-shadow nodes — for example appending children or setting attributes, styling individual nodes using element.style.foo, or adding style to the entire shadow DOM tree inside a `<style>` element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The difference is that none of the code inside a shadow DOM can affect anything outside it, allowing for handy encapsulation.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Before shadow DOM was made available to web developers, browsers were already using it to encapsulate the inner structure of an element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Think for example of a `<video>` element, with the default browser controls exposed.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] All you see in the DOM is the `<video>` element, but it contains a series of buttons and other controls inside its shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The shadow DOM spec enables you to manipulate the shadow DOM of your own custom elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The shadow tree and `<slot>` elements inherit the `dir` and `lang` attributes from their shadow host.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] We're going to use the `"host"` element as the shadow host.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] We call `attachShadow()` on the host to create the shadow DOM, and can then add nodes to the shadow DOM just like we would to the main DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Creating a shadow DOM via JavaScript API might be a good option for client-side rendered applications.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] For other applications, a server-side rendered UI might have better performance and, therefore, a better user experience.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] In such cases, you can use the `<template>` element to declaratively define the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The key to this behavior is the enumerated `shadowrootmode` attribute, which can be set to either `open` or `closed`, the same values as the `mode` option of `attachShadow()` method.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] After the browser parses the HTML, it replaces `<template>` element with its content wrapped in a shadow root that's attached to the parent element, the `<div id="host">` in our example.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Note that in addition to the `shadowrootmode`, you can use `<template>` attributes such as `shadowrootclonable` and `shadowrootdelegatesfocus` to specify other properties of the generated shadow root.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] But let's see what happens if code running in the page tries to access elements in the shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] This page is just like the last one, except we've added two `<button>` elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Clicking the "Uppercase span elements" button finds all `<span>` elements in the page and changes their text to uppercase.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Clicking the "Reload" button just reloads the page, so you can try again.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] In the example above, we pass an argument `{ mode: "open" }` to `attachShadow()`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] With `mode` set to `"open"`, the JavaScript in the page is able to access the internals of your shadow DOM through the `shadowRoot` property of the shadow host.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The `{mode: "open"}` argument gives the page a way to break the encapsulation of your shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] If you don't want to give the page this ability, pass `{mode: "closed"}` instead, and then `shadowRoot` returns `null`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] However, you should not consider this a strong security mechanism, because there are ways it can be evaded, for example by browser extensions running in the page.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] It's more of an indication that the page should not access the internals of your shadow DOM tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] In both cases, the styles defined in the shadow DOM tree are scoped to that tree, so just as page styles don't affect elements in the shadow DOM, shadow DOM styles don't affect elements in the rest of the page.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Rules defined in the `CSSStyleSheet` will be scoped to the shadow DOM tree, as well as any other DOM trees to which we have assigned it.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] An alternative to constructing `CSSStyleSheet` objects is to include a `<style>` element inside the `<template>` element used to define a web component.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Which of these options to use is dependent on your application and personal preference.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Creating a `CSSStyleSheet` and assigning it to the shadow root using `adoptedStyleSheets` allows you to create a single stylesheet and share it among many DOM trees.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] For example, a component library could create a single stylesheet and then share it among all the custom elements belonging to that library.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The browser will parse that stylesheet once.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Also, you can make dynamic changes to the stylesheet and have them propagate to all components that use the sheet.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The approach of attaching a `<style>` element is great if you want to be declarative, have few styles, and don't need to share styles across different components.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Without the encapsulation provided by shadow DOM, custom elements would be impossibly fragile.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] It would be too easy for a page to accidentally break a custom element's behavior or layout by running some page JavaScript or CSS.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] As a custom element developer, you'd never know whether the selectors applicable inside your custom element conflicted with those that applied in a page that chose to use your custom element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Custom elements are implemented as a class which extends either the base `HTMLElement` or a built-in HTML element such as `HTMLParagraphElement`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] Typically, the custom element itself is a shadow host, and the element creates multiple elements under that root, to provide the internal implementation of the element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] The example below creates a `<filled-circle>` custom element that just renders a circle filled with a solid color.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-shadow-dom] For more examples, illustrating different aspects of custom element implementation, see our guide to custom elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This article explains how you can use the `<template>` and `<slot>` elements to create a flexible template that can then be used to populate the shadow DOM of a web component.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] When you have to reuse the same markup structures repeatedly on a web page, it makes sense to use some kind of a template rather than repeating the same structure over and over again.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This was possible before, but it is made a lot easier by the HTML `<template>` element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This element and its contents are not rendered in the DOM, but it can still be referenced using JavaScript.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Although trivial, you can already start to see how this could be useful.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Templates are useful on their own, but they work even better with web components.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Let's define a web component that uses our template as the content of its shadow DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] The key point to note here is that we append a clone of the template content to the shadow root, created using the `Document.importNode()` method.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] And because we are appending its contents to a shadow DOM, we can include some styling information inside the template in a `<style>` element, which is then encapsulated inside the custom element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This wouldn't work if we just appended it to the standard DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] So far so good, but the element isn't very flexible.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] We can only display one bit of text inside it, meaning that at the moment it is even less useful than a regular paragraph!
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] We can make it possible to display different text in each element instance in a nice declarative way using the `<slot>` element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Slots are identified by their `name` attribute, and allow you to define placeholders in your template that can be filled with any markup fragment you want when the element is used in the markup.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] If the slot's content isn't defined when the element is included in the markup, or if the browser doesn't support slots, `<my-paragraph>` just contains the fallback content "My default text".
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] To define the slot's content, we include an HTML structure inside the `<my-paragraph>` element with a `slot` attribute whose value is equal to the name of the slot we want it to fill.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] If you want to play with it some more, you can find it on GitHub (see it running live also).
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] The `name` attribute should be unique per shadow root: if you have two slots with the same name, all of the elements with a matching `slot` attribute will be assigned to the first slot with that name.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] But the `slot` attribute does not need to be unique: a `<slot>` can be filled by multiple elements that all have a matching `slot` attribute.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] The `name` and `slot` attributes both default to the empty string, so elements with no `slot` attributes are assigned to the `<slot>` with no `name` attribute (the unnamed slot, or default slot).
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] The previous example uses *named slot assignment*, which means the named `<slot>` elements in a template are populated with the content of elements in the custom component (or more generally the host element) that have matching names in their `slot` attributes.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This is the original mechanism used for slot assignment and is the most suitable method for most use cases.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Manual assignment is useful when you want to dynamically select the content to be slotted, or if you want to assign slots based on some other element attribute such as their `id`, without having to add duplicate `slot` attributes.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] For example, a `<movie-picker>` custom element might use a `<select>` element to filter on genre, slotting only the elements that have a matching `data-genre` attribute value on change.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Named slot assignment is the default behavior.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] On user agents that support setting the shadow root slot assignment method, you can enable this feature when you attach the shadow root.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This is done programmatically using the `options.slotAssignment` parameter passed to `Element.attachShadow()`, or declaratively by setting the `shadowrootslotassignment` attribute on the `<template>` element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] The following HTML shows a basic example of how you can set `shadowrootslotassignment` when declaratively creating a shadow root (using `shadowrootmode`).
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] To finish off the article, let's look at something a little less trivial.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] However, it is generally more practical to add slots within a `<template>` element, since you are unlikely to need to define a pattern based on an already-rendered element.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] In addition, even if it is not already rendered, the purpose of the container as a template should be more semantically clear when using the `<template>`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] In addition, `<template>` can have items directly added to it, like `<td>`, which would disappear when added to a `<div>`.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Next, let's create a new custom element named **`<element-details>`** and use `Element.attachShadow` to attach to it, as its shadow root, that document fragment we created with our `<template>` element above.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] This uses exactly the same pattern as we saw in our earlier trivial example.
[src:web-components-advanced/using-templates-and-slots] Finally let's put all the snippets together and see what the rendered result looks like.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:web-components-advanced/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
